RustAssets --> RustCore
RustLlm --> RustCore
RustIntegrations --> RustCore

' Guardrails apply to source graph, not runtime calls
DepCruise .[#558B2F].> SharedFrontend : forbids shared -> features/app
DepCruise .[#558B2F].> Ports : forbids engine -> React/Zustand/Tauri adapters
DepCruise .[#558B2F].> ModeSurface : forbids mode cross-imports and private feature internals
Eslint .[#558B2F].> SharedFrontend
Eslint .[#558B2F].> ChatEngine
RustStructure .[#558B2F].> ImportModules
CI .[#558B2F].> DepCruise
CI .[#558B2F].> Eslint
CI .[#558B2F].> RustStructure

' Remaining pressure is responsibility concentration, not currently failed dependency rules
ModeSurface -[#C62828,dashed]-> ModeSurface : router also owns chat loading,\ngeneration flow, sprite metadata,\nTTS/translation, agent review,\nworld-state refresh
GameSurface -[#C62828,dashed]-> GameSurface : UI, state sync, game effects,\nassets, audio, Spotify, sprites,\nNPC avatars, narration progress,\nmetadata persistence
SharedModeUI -[#C62828,dashed]-> SharedModeUI : some shared mode UI files are large,\nnot boundary violations
CommandRegistry -[#F9A825,dashed]-> CommandRegistry : centralized command list remains broad
ImportModules -[#F9A825,dashed]-> ImportModules : import workflows are split,\nbut bulk/marinara modules are still dense

note top of DepCruise
  Current validation result:
  pnpm.cmd check passed.
  dependency-cruiser reported zero dependency violations
  across 568 modules and 2019 dependencies.
end note

note right of ModeSurface
  This is no longer mainly a package-boundary problem.
  The problem is density: one React file still coordinates
  several feature concerns that could have mode-owned controllers.
end note

note right of GameSurface
  This is the largest remaining mismatch with the original sketch.
  The engine and package boundaries are modular,
  but the game UI surface is still a very large orchestrator.
end note

note bottom of SharedFrontend
  The previous shared-layer inversion appears addressed:
  src/shared is guarded from importing src/features or src/app.
end note

note bottom of ImportModules
  The previous Rust import blob is substantially improved:
  commands are thin and imports are split into service,
  normalization, payloads, Marinara, preset, timestamps,
  access, and bulk import modules.
end note

@enduml
